    <h2>1. Why Commercial Kitchen Ventilation Is Non-Negotiable in India</h2>

    <p>Walk into any busy restaurant kitchen in India without proper ventilation and the problems are immediately obvious: grease-coated walls and ceilings, staff drenched in sweat, cooking smoke drifting into the dining area, and a persistent fire hazard building inside neglected ductwork. These are not cosmetic issues — they are safety, legal, and business risks.</p>

    <h3>Legal Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>FSSAI licensing (mandatory for all food businesses)</strong> requires demonstration of adequate ventilation as a basic hygiene condition. Inspectors physically verify functional exhaust systems during licence inspections and renewals. No working exhaust system means no licence — or licence suspension at renewal.</li>
      <li><strong>Fire NOC from local fire departments</strong> mandates kitchen exhaust systems meeting National Building Code (NBC) 2016 standards. For kitchens with deep fryers, tandoors, or solid-fuel equipment, integrated fire suppression is required. Without a fire NOC, you cannot legally operate a commercial establishment in most Indian cities.</li>
      <li><strong>Pollution NOC from State Pollution Control Boards</strong> is increasingly enforced for commercial kitchens in metros. Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, and Chennai now require kitchens above certain sizes to demonstrate exhaust treatment (electrostatic precipitators or scrubbers) before discharge. Non-compliance can result in closure orders.</li>
      <li><strong>Municipal trade licences</strong> in major cities require proof of functional kitchen ventilation as a condition of issuance.</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance policies</strong> for commercial kitchen fire and liability coverage often require compliant exhaust and fire suppression systems. A claim on a kitchen fire may be denied if your ventilation system was non-compliant.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Operational Impact</h3>
    <p>Beyond compliance, proper ventilation transforms kitchen operations. Cooking line temperatures drop by 5–10 degrees Celsius with good exhaust, reducing staff fatigue and heat-related illness during Indian summers. Grease deposition on surfaces drops by 80–90%, cutting cleaning time and extending equipment life. And a well-maintained ventilation system is the single most effective fire prevention measure in any commercial kitchen — grease-laden ductwork is the number one cause of commercial kitchen fires in India.</p>

    <h2>2. Exhaust Hood Types for Indian Commercial Kitchens</h2>

    <p>The exhaust hood is the visible centrepiece of your ventilation system — the canopy that captures smoke, steam, grease vapour, and heat rising from cooking equipment. Choosing the right hood type depends on your kitchen layout, equipment placement, and cooking intensity.</p>

    <h3>Wall-Mount Canopy Hood</h3>
    <p>The most common exhaust hood in Indian commercial kitchens. It mounts against a wall with the cooking equipment positioned below. One side (the wall) provides a natural capture boundary, making wall-mount hoods 20–30% more efficient per unit of airflow than island hoods covering the same equipment. Wall-mount hoods suit tandoor stations, gas ranges, woks, fryers, and griddles placed against walls — which describes the majority of Indian restaurant kitchens.</p>
    <p><strong>Sizing rule:</strong> The hood must overhang cooking equipment by at least 150 mm (6 inches) on all open sides. For high-heat equipment like tandoors, increase to 300 mm. Price range: ₹18,000–₹80,000 for a 1.2 m to 3 m wide hood in SS 304.</p>

    <h3>Island (Ceiling-Mounted) Canopy Hood</h3>
    <p>Suspended from the ceiling over a central cooking island. Open on all four sides, so it requires 20–30% more CFM than a wall-mount hood for the same equipment. Island hoods are the right choice when your kitchen layout places equipment in the centre — common in open-plan kitchens, modern cloud kitchens, and show-kitchen concepts. They cost more (₹45,000–₹1,80,000), need structural ceiling support, and require longer duct runs. But for central-island layouts, they are the only effective option.</p>

    <h3>Low-Profile Proximity Hood</h3>
    <p>Positioned close to equipment rather than high above it. Best for steam-producing equipment: commercial dishwashers, combi-steamers, bain-maries. Proximity hoods use significantly less airflow because they capture contaminants before the plume rises and disperses. Not appropriate for fryers, tandoors, or open-flame cooking. Price range: ₹15,000–₹45,000.</p>

    <h3>Backshelf Hood</h3>
    <p>A compact hood positioned at the back of a cooking line rather than overhead. Suitable for light-duty cooking in cafes and small QSRs. Low airflow requirement keeps energy costs down, but backshelf hoods are inadequate for heavy grease-producing equipment. Price range: ₹12,000–₹35,000.</p>

    <h3>Make-Up Air (MUA) Integrated Hood</h3>
    <p>In sealed commercial spaces — basement restaurants, fully air-conditioned kitchens, cloud kitchens in office buildings — a standard exhaust hood removes more air than can naturally infiltrate. The result: negative pressure, doors difficult to open, hood capture efficiency drops, and HVAC systems strain. An MUA-integrated hood supplies tempered fresh air directly into the hood plenum as exhaust air is removed, maintaining pressure balance. Essential in any enclosed Indian kitchen where natural air replacement is insufficient. Price range: ₹85,000–₹3,00,000.</p>

    <h3>Hood with Integrated Fire Suppression</h3>
    <p>Any hood over deep fryers, tandoors, or solid-fuel equipment should include an integrated wet chemical fire suppression system (ANSUL-type). The system automatically detects fire via fusible links and discharges wet chemical agent onto the cooking surface and into the duct. Required by fire departments for Fire NOC in most Indian cities. Price range: ₹1,20,000–₹3,00,000+ installed.</p>

    <h2>3. Exhaust Fan Types &amp; Selection for Commercial Kitchens</h2>

    <p>The exhaust fan is the engine of your ventilation system — it creates the airflow that pulls cooking effluent through the hood, into the ductwork, and out of the building. Choosing the right fan type, capacity, and placement is as important as choosing the right hood.</p>

    <h3>Centrifugal (Belt-Drive or Direct-Drive) Exhaust Fans</h3>
    <p>The standard for commercial kitchen exhaust in India. Centrifugal fans produce high static pressure, which is essential for overcoming resistance in ductwork — especially in kitchens with long duct runs, multiple bends, or rooftop discharge. Belt-drive models allow speed adjustment (by changing pulley ratios) and are easier to maintain. Direct-drive models are quieter and more compact but offer less flexibility. For most Indian commercial kitchens, a belt-drive centrifugal fan rated for grease-laden air is the correct choice.</p>

    <h3>Axial Fans</h3>
    <p>Move large volumes of air at low static pressure. Axial fans are suitable only for short, straight duct runs (under 3 metres) with minimal resistance — wall-mount units that exhaust directly through an adjacent wall, for instance. They are cheaper (₹4,000–₹15,000) but inadequate for most commercial kitchen installations where duct runs are longer and bends are unavoidable. Do not use axial fans for kitchens with rooftop exhaust discharge.</p>

    <h3>Inline Duct Fans</h3>
    <p>Installed within the ductwork rather than at the terminal point. Inline fans are used as booster fans in long duct runs or as the primary fan in small installations with very short runs. They save space compared to external centrifugal units but are harder to service (you need to access the duct interior). Useful in cloud kitchens and small QSRs with space constraints.</p>

