    <h2>4. CFM Calculation for Indian Commercial Kitchens</h2>

    <p>CFM (Cubic Feet per Minute) is the standard measure of exhaust airflow. Getting this calculation right is the foundation of an effective ventilation system. Too little CFM and the hood fails to capture cooking effluent — smoke escapes, grease deposits on walls, and the kitchen overheats. Too much CFM wastes electricity, creates uncomfortable draughts, and can over-pressurise the kitchen if make-up air is not balanced.</p>

    <h3>The Standard Formula</h3>
    <p>The most widely used method in India, aligned with NBC 2016 and ASHRAE Standard 154:</p>
    <p><strong>CFM = Hood Length (feet) x CFM per Linear Foot</strong></p>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Equipment Category</th><th>CFM/ft (Wall-Mount Hood)</th><th>CFM/ft (Island Hood)</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Light duty</td><td>150 – 200</td><td>200 – 250</td><td>Steamers, bain-marie, pasta cooker</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Medium duty</td><td>200 – 300</td><td>275 – 375</td><td>Gas range, griddle, convection oven</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Heavy duty</td><td>300 – 400</td><td>400 – 500</td><td>Wok, deep fryer, charbroiler</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Extra-heavy duty</td><td>400 – 550</td><td>550 – 700</td><td>Tandoor, solid fuel, coal grill</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Worked Example: Medium Restaurant Kitchen</h3>
    <p>A wall-mount hood over an 8-foot cooking line with 4 gas burners, 1 deep fryer, and 1 griddle (heavy duty category):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Hood length: 8 ft equipment + 1 ft overhang each side = 10 ft hood</li>
      <li>CFM factor: 350 CFM/ft (mid-range heavy duty)</li>
      <li>Required CFM: 10 ft x 350 = <strong>3,500 CFM</strong></li>
      <li>With 15% safety margin: 3,500 x 1.15 = <strong>4,025 CFM</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p>Convert to SI: 4,025 CFM x 1.699 = <strong>6,838 m³/hr</strong> — select a 7,000 m³/hr rated centrifugal fan.</p>

    <h3>Face Velocity Check</h3>
    <p>The air velocity at the hood opening should be 0.25–0.5 m/s for most applications. Exceeding 0.5 m/s creates turbulence that can reduce capture efficiency. If face velocity is too high, increase hood size rather than reducing fan speed — a larger hood at moderate velocity always outperforms a smaller hood at high velocity.</p>

    <h2>5. Ductwork Design &amp; Materials</h2>

    <p>Ductwork connects the exhaust hood to the exhaust fan and terminates at the discharge point (typically the roof or an external wall). Duct design affects system performance, noise, maintenance cost, and fire safety.</p>

    <h3>Material Selection</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Galvanised Iron (GI):</strong> The standard ductwork material for commercial kitchens in India. GI is cost-effective, readily available, and adequate for most installations. Minimum 22-gauge (0.8 mm) for ducts up to 450 mm diameter; 20-gauge (1.0 mm) for larger ducts. GI ducts must be welded at seams — riveted joints trap grease and are a fire hazard.</li>
      <li><strong>Stainless Steel (SS 304):</strong> Used for the first 1–2 metres of duct from the hood (the grease-heaviest section) and for exposed ductwork in open kitchens. More expensive than GI but resists corrosion from grease acids and cleaning chemicals. Required in some high-end hotel specifications.</li>
      <li><strong>Black steel (MS):</strong> Used by some contractors as a cheaper alternative. Acceptable for external ductwork but rusts when exposed to grease and moisture. Not recommended for internal ductwork in commercial kitchens.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Duct Design Best Practices</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Keep duct runs as short and straight as possible. Every 90-degree bend adds 5–8 metres of equivalent duct length (resistance), requiring more fan power.</li>
      <li>Maintain a minimum duct velocity of 7.5–10 m/s to prevent grease settling in horizontal runs.</li>
      <li>Slope horizontal duct runs 2–3 degrees back toward the hood for grease drainage.</li>
      <li>Install cleanout access panels every 3 metres and at every bend — mandatory for fire compliance and practical for maintenance.</li>
      <li>Seal all joints with high-temperature sealant. Grease leaks at duct joints are a fire risk and a hygiene violation.</li>
      <li>Terminate exhaust discharge at least 3 metres from any air intake, window, or occupied space. In residential-area restaurants, install the discharge at rooftop height to avoid nuisance complaints.</li>
    </ul>

