    <h2>6. Make-Up Air (MUA) Systems</h2>

    <p>Every cubic metre of air your exhaust fan removes must be replaced. If replacement air cannot enter the kitchen naturally (through doors, windows, and building gaps), the kitchen develops negative pressure: doors are hard to open, the exhaust hood loses capture efficiency (air currents disrupt the capture plume), and the HVAC system strains to compensate. In India, this is an especially acute problem in basement kitchens, air-conditioned commercial complexes, and malls.</p>

    <h3>When Do You Need a Dedicated MUA System?</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Kitchen is in a basement or sealed commercial space with no natural air pathways</li>
      <li>Kitchen is in an air-conditioned building where opening windows is not practical</li>
      <li>Total exhaust CFM exceeds 2,000 and the space has limited natural infiltration</li>
      <li>You notice doors slamming, difficulty opening entry doors, or exhaust hood inefficiency at peak cooking loads</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>MUA System Options</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Passive MUA:</strong> Louvers or transfer grilles in exterior walls or ceilings that allow air to flow in naturally as the exhaust creates negative pressure. Cost: ₹5,000–₹20,000. Suitable for small kitchens with short exhaust runs.</li>
      <li><strong>Powered MUA (fan-driven):</strong> A supply fan pushes fresh air into the kitchen, sometimes through a tempered air unit that heats or cools the incoming air. Required for most medium and large kitchens. Cost: ₹40,000–₹2,00,000 depending on capacity.</li>
      <li><strong>Hood-integrated MUA:</strong> Fresh air is delivered directly into the hood plenum — the most efficient approach, as the replacement air is delivered exactly where the exhaust air is being removed. Cost: ₹85,000–₹3,00,000 as part of an MUA hood unit.</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> MUA supply should deliver 80–90% of exhaust volume. The remaining 10–20% deficit maintains slight negative pressure in the kitchen — which prevents cooking odours from escaping to the dining area. A perfectly balanced (100%) system or a positive-pressure kitchen pushes cooking smells into the dining room.</p>

    <h2>7. Grease Trap Systems for Commercial Kitchens in India</h2>

    <p>A grease trap is a plumbing device that intercepts fats, oils, and grease (FOG) from wastewater before it enters the municipal sewer system. While not strictly part of the exhaust ventilation system, grease traps are a closely related component of commercial kitchen waste management — and they are increasingly mandatory in Indian cities.</p>

    <h3>Why Grease Traps Are Mandatory</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Municipal regulations:</strong> Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, Hyderabad, Chennai, and Pune now require commercial kitchens to install grease traps. The CPCB (Central Pollution Control Board) guidelines specify maximum FOG discharge limits for food establishments.</li>
      <li><strong>FSSAI compliance:</strong> FSSAI inspectors check for proper wastewater management, including grease interception, during licence audits.</li>
      <li><strong>Sewer blockage prevention:</strong> FOG is the leading cause of sewer blockages in commercial areas. Municipalities are actively enforcing grease trap requirements to protect sewer infrastructure.</li>
      <li><strong>Pollution NOC:</strong> Your State Pollution Control Board NOC application will require documentation of FOG management measures.</li>
    </ul>

