    <h2>8. Fire Suppression Systems for Kitchen Exhaust Hoods</h2>

    <p>Commercial kitchen fires account for a disproportionate share of fire incidents in Indian commercial buildings, and grease fires in exhaust ductwork are the leading cause. A wet chemical fire suppression system integrated with your exhaust hood is both a legal requirement (for Fire NOC) and a genuine life-safety investment.</p>

    <h3>How Wet Chemical Fire Suppression Works</h3>
    <p>The system consists of fusible links mounted in the hood and duct that melt at a pre-set temperature (typically 182 degrees Celsius). When a link melts, it triggers the release of a wet chemical fire suppressant (potassium carbonate or acetate solution) through nozzles aimed at the cooking surface and duct interior. The chemical saponifies burning grease — converting it into a non-combustible soap-like substance — and simultaneously smothers the fire. The system also shuts off fuel supply (gas valve) and exhaust fan automatically.</p>

    <h3>When Is Fire Suppression Legally Required?</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Any kitchen operating deep fryers (most common requirement)</li>
      <li>Tandoor or solid-fuel cooking equipment</li>
      <li>Charcoal or wood-fired grills</li>
      <li>Kitchens in commercial complexes, malls, or high-rise buildings (typically mandated by fire department regardless of equipment type)</li>
      <li>Any kitchen requiring a Fire NOC (which is most commercial kitchens in urban India)</li>
    </ul>

