    <p>Leading brands in India: Ansul (Tyco/Johnson Controls), Lehavot, Amerex, and domestic manufacturers like Ceasefire and Minimax. Always use a licensed installer — the fire department will verify installation certification during NOC inspection.</p>

    <h2>9. HVAC Coordination &amp; Kitchen Cooling</h2>

    <p>In India, where kitchen ambient temperatures routinely exceed 40 degrees Celsius in summer, HVAC coordination with the exhaust system is critical. The exhaust system removes hot air — but it also removes the air your HVAC system has cooled. Without coordination, you either overcool the dining area to compensate (wasting electricity) or undercool the kitchen (compromising staff safety and food quality).</p>

    <h3>Best Practices for HVAC-Ventilation Coordination</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Tempered make-up air:</strong> Supply replacement air that is partially cooled (to 28–30 degrees Celsius rather than ambient 40+ degrees Celsius). This reduces the cooling load on the kitchen HVAC without the expense of full air-conditioning the make-up air stream.</li>
      <li><strong>Kitchen-dining pressure management:</strong> Keep the kitchen at slight negative pressure (10–15 Pa below dining area) to prevent cooking odours from migrating. This is achieved by exhausting slightly more air than you supply.</li>
      <li><strong>Spot cooling:</strong> Position small air-conditioning units or evaporative coolers at specific workstations (prep tables, plating stations) rather than trying to cool the entire kitchen evenly. The cooking line will always be hot — focus cooling where staff stand for extended periods.</li>
      <li><strong>Air curtains:</strong> Install air curtains at the kitchen-dining interface to maintain temperature separation without physical doors. Cost: ₹8,000–₹25,000 per unit.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>10. Pollution NOC &amp; Regulatory Compliance</h2>

    <p>Pollution NOC requirements for commercial kitchens have tightened significantly across Indian metros in 2025–2026. The key regulatory bodies are State Pollution Control Boards (SPCBs), which operate under CPCB (Central Pollution Control Board) guidelines.</p>

    <h3>What the Pollution NOC Requires</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Exhaust treatment:</strong> In Delhi (DPCC), Mumbai (MPCB), and several other metros, commercial kitchens above certain sizes must install an Electrostatic Precipitator (ESP) or wet scrubber to treat exhaust air before discharge. This removes grease particles and smoke from the exhaust stream, reducing air pollution.</li>
      <li><strong>Grease trap documentation:</strong> Proof that a functional grease trap is installed and regularly maintained.</li>
      <li><strong>Noise limits:</strong> Exhaust fans must comply with noise standards (typically 75 dB at 1 metre for industrial zones, 65 dB for commercial zones). Centrifugal fans with acoustic enclosures or attenuators may be needed in noise-sensitive locations.</li>
      <li><strong>Discharge height:</strong> Exhaust must discharge at specified heights above building level to ensure adequate dispersion.</li>
    </ul>

