    <h2>12. Installation Best Practices</h2>

    <p>A perfectly specified ventilation system can fail if installation is poor. These are the most common installation mistakes we see in Indian commercial kitchens — and how to avoid them.</p>

    <h3>Common Installation Mistakes</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Undersized ductwork:</strong> Contractors sometimes use smaller ducts to save material. Undersized ducts increase air velocity excessively, cause noise, and reduce system lifespan. Insist on duct sizes specified in the ventilation design — do not allow field changes.</li>
      <li><strong>Too many bends:</strong> Each 90-degree bend costs you 5–8 metres of equivalent duct length. Poorly routed ducts with multiple bends drastically reduce system performance. Plan duct routes during kitchen design, not after construction.</li>
      <li><strong>No access panels:</strong> Ducts without cleanout panels cannot be professionally cleaned. Fire NOC inspectors will flag this. Insist on access panels every 3 metres and at every bend.</li>
      <li><strong>Riveted joints instead of welded:</strong> Riveted duct seams trap grease and eventually leak. All grease-carrying ductwork must be continuously welded.</li>
      <li><strong>Fan placed indoors:</strong> The exhaust fan should ideally be placed at the building exterior (rooftop or external wall) so that the entire duct run is under negative pressure. An indoor fan means any duct leak between the fan and discharge point pushes contaminated air into the building.</li>
      <li><strong>No make-up air provision:</strong> Contractors install the exhaust system without considering air replacement. The result is negative pressure, hood inefficiency, and HVAC problems. Always include MUA in your ventilation design.</li>
      <li><strong>Inadequate hood overhang:</strong> The hood must overhang cooking equipment by at least 150 mm on all open sides. A hood that is flush with the equipment edge will not capture cooking effluent effectively.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Installation Timeline</h3>
    <p>A complete ventilation system installation (hood + ductwork + fan + MUA + grease trap + fire suppression) takes 5–12 days for a medium-size restaurant kitchen. Plan for this in your project timeline — ventilation installation should happen after civil work and plumbing but before final electrical and HVAC commissioning. Coordinate with your general contractor to avoid sequencing conflicts.</p>

    <h2>13. Maintenance Schedule for Commercial Kitchen Ventilation</h2>

    <p>A neglected ventilation system is a fire hazard, a health code violation, and an operational liability. Grease-laden ductwork is the leading cause of commercial kitchen fires. Maintain your system on a strict schedule.</p>

    <h3>Daily</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Wipe hood exterior surfaces with degreasing solution</li>
      <li>Empty grease collection troughs/cups if more than half full</li>
      <li>Check that exhaust fan is running normally (no unusual noise or vibration)</li>
      <li>Verify fire suppression fusible links are in place</li>
      <li>Clean grease trap strainer basket</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Weekly</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Remove and soak grease filters in hot water with commercial degreaser (minimum 20 minutes), scrub, rinse, and reinstall</li>
      <li>Clean hood interior surfaces and grease baffles</li>
      <li>Inspect first metre of duct at hood connection for grease build-up</li>
      <li>Check exhaust fan motor for noise or vibration; inspect belt tension on belt-drive fans</li>
      <li>Pump grease trap (for high-volume kitchens)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Inspect duct run via access panels for grease accumulation</li>
      <li>Check hood suspension bolts and ceiling mounts</li>
      <li>Test fire suppression manual pull station</li>
      <li>Clean ESP collector plates (if installed)</li>
      <li>Pump grease trap (for moderate-volume kitchens)</li>
      <li>Log inspection in maintenance record</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Quarterly</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Professional high-pressure duct cleaning for heavy-grease equipment (fryers, tandoors)</li>
      <li>Fan wheel and housing cleaning by qualified technician</li>
      <li>Fire suppression visual inspection by certified technician</li>
      <li>MUA filter replacement</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Annually</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Complete duct cleaning with post-clean inspection report (required for Fire NOC renewal)</li>
      <li>Fire suppression full service (agent level check, nozzle inspection, control system test)</li>
      <li>Fan motor service (bearing lubrication, belt replacement)</li>
      <li>Hood structural inspection (welds, mounts, corrosion)</li>
      <li>ESP professional deep clean and calibration</li>
      <li>Update maintenance log for regulatory documentation</li>
    </ul>

