    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What size exhaust fan do I need for my commercial kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">The required exhaust fan size depends on your hood dimensions and cooking equipment intensity. Use the formula: Hood Length (feet) x CFM per linear foot. For medium-duty cooking (gas ranges, griddles), use 200–300 CFM/ft for wall-mount hoods. For heavy duty (fryers, woks), use 300–400 CFM/ft. For tandoors and solid fuel, use 400–550 CFM/ft. Convert to m³/hr by multiplying CFM by 1.699. A typical 6-foot cooking line with a gas range and fryer needs approximately 2,500–3,500 CFM (4,200–6,000 m³/hr). Always select a fan rated 10–15% above calculated requirement for safety margin.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Is a grease trap mandatory for restaurants in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes, in most metro cities. Delhi (DPCC), Mumbai (MPCB), Bengaluru (KSPCB), Hyderabad, Chennai, and Pune now require commercial food establishments to install functional grease traps. FSSAI also checks for proper wastewater management during licence inspections. Even in cities where enforcement is developing, installing a grease trap is strongly recommended — municipal penalties for sewer blockage caused by FOG from commercial kitchens are increasing. A basic under-sink SS grease trap costs ₹6,000–₹15,000 and is a worthwhile investment for any commercial kitchen.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the cost of a complete commercial kitchen ventilation system in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A complete ventilation system (exhaust hood, fan, ductwork, make-up air, grease trap, and installation) costs ₹1.5–4 lakh for a small kitchen (cloud kitchen, small QSR), ₹3.5–8 lakh for a medium restaurant kitchen, and ₹7.5–20+ lakh for a large restaurant or hotel kitchen. Add ₹0.8–5 lakh for fire suppression if required. These are 2026 prices including supply and installation. Metro cities cost 15–25% more than Tier-2 cities due to higher labour and compliance requirements.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do I need a pollution NOC for my restaurant kitchen? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">In most Indian metro cities, yes. State Pollution Control Boards increasingly require commercial kitchens to obtain a Consent to Operate (CTO) which functions as a pollution NOC. Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, and Chennai actively enforce this. Requirements typically include an electrostatic precipitator (ESP) or wet scrubber on your exhaust, a functional grease trap, and compliance with noise limits. Application fees range from ₹5,000 to ₹25,000 depending on state and establishment size. Non-compliance can result in closure orders.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the difference between a centrifugal and axial exhaust fan for a commercial kitchen? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">A centrifugal fan generates high static pressure, making it suitable for duct runs with bends, long distances, and rooftop discharge — the standard for most commercial kitchen installations. An axial fan moves large air volumes at low pressure and is only suitable for very short, straight duct runs (direct wall exhaust) or as a booster. For any kitchen with ductwork exceeding 3 metres or with bends in the duct route, use a centrifugal fan. Always specify a grease-rated fan designed for commercial kitchen use — standard ventilation fans will fail quickly in grease-laden air.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How do I get a Fire NOC for my restaurant kitchen in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Apply through your local fire department or the state fire services portal. Requirements typically include: a functional exhaust system meeting NBC 2016 standards, fire suppression on hoods over fryers and solid-fuel equipment, fire extinguishers (ABC type, one per 100 sq ft of kitchen), emergency exits, and fire-rated construction. Submit your kitchen layout, ventilation system specifications, fire suppression installation certificate, and fire extinguisher maintenance records. The fire department conducts a physical inspection before issuance. Fees range from ₹2,000 to ₹15,000 depending on establishment size and city. For more on licensing, see our <a href="/blog/fssai-license-cost-registration-india">FSSAI licence and registration guide</a>.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How often should commercial kitchen exhaust ducts be cleaned? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">Cleaning frequency depends on equipment type. Kitchens with deep fryers running 12+ hours daily: monthly duct cleaning. Kitchens with fryers on limited hours, tandoors, woks, and charbroilers: quarterly. Light cooking only (steamers, bain-maries): semi-annually. Grease filters should be washed weekly regardless of equipment type. Maintain a written cleaning log — fire departments and FSSAI inspectors request this during inspections and licence renewals. Professional duct cleaning costs ₹5,000–₹25,000 per session depending on duct length and accessibility.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can I use a residential exhaust fan in a commercial kitchen? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a">No. Residential exhaust fans are not designed for grease-laden air, lack the static pressure to move air through ductwork, and will fail within weeks to months in a commercial kitchen environment. Their motors are not sealed against grease infiltration, their blades accumulate grease rapidly, and they do not meet the airflow requirements of any commercial kitchen — even a small one. Always use a grease-rated commercial exhaust fan. Entry-level commercial fans from brands like Almonard or Havells start at ₹4,000–₹8,000 — the small additional cost over a residential fan avoids equipment failure, fire risk, and non-compliance.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

